defaultOf necessity considerable energy has been expended in building the foundations from which to operate in what is a wholly new landscape.
default&#xa0;
default2.0default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe effectiveness of Commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police force in their area.default&#xa0;default2.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPolicing represents only part, albeit a very important part, of a collective effort to reduce crime. There is a wide diversity of work undertaken in this area, whether in prisons, by probation, by the ‘troubled families’ programmes, by police officers and others. PCCs have responsibility across the entire criminal justice landscape at a local level and so make considerable efforts to join the disparate parts of it together and make it as effective as possible. However given that each component of this complex system is being squeezed financially, the gaps are widening whilst the dependencies become more acute.
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDetailed analysis of performance data is used to ask questions and arrive at imaginative ways to address the upward pressure on reported crime. When shop theft was on the increase a summit was held to identify creative solutions to business crime. The PCC was a champion for local initiatives developed and delivered by the Middlesbrough Retail Crime Partnership and ‘Redcar Shop Link’ Scheme. Analysis showed a move away from stealing items to sell, to stealing food and essentials. Food banks have been supported and promoted by the PCC where essentials such as groceries and baby formula were the main items stolen. 
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWith ‘other theft’ on the increase due to fraud offences, the PCC is taking the opportunity in the run up to Christmas to share fraud prevention advice through a series of public consultation 
defaultroadshows
default in town centres. 
default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAnalysis of the 
defaultdisproportionate involvement of people with mental health problems held (under section 136) in custody led to a ‘street triage’ approach involving the NHS and 
defaultp
defaultolice. This has 
defaultreduced 
defaultthe number
defaults
default detained unnecessarily and the level of reoffending within this cohort, whilst reducing the pressure on 
defaultpolice resources and allocating the identified mental health need into the correct care pathway. 
defaultOther forces are now adopting this approach.
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default 
default              
defaultWhen police are called to an address or incident and believe that an individual involved has a mental disorder, learning disability or substance misuse problem, they contact the 
defaultmental health 
defaultnurses 
defaultwho
default carry out an assessment. Th
defaultis 
defaultinforms further care planning, ascertaining whether the person needs to be held under s136 and if not, whether follow up from mental health, social or substance misuse services is required. The nursing team refer to those services if required, provide information to service users about relevant agencies and where appropriate, provide follow up appointments within seven days of the assessment.      
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
