default2.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRestorative Justice has been developed 
defaultby the PCC working with the force to 
defaultdeal with
default crime, anti-social behaviour and ‘conflict’ in communities.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultFrom 1st April 2013 across 
defaultCleveland
default most offences of crime, anti-social behaviour and disorder committed by young people under the age of 18, who have not previously come to the attention of the police 
defaultare
default resolved by way of a Restorative Intervention (RI).
default&#xa0;
default The RI will usually take place within the community, led by a police officer, PCSO or police staff member and will be swift, effective, sustainable and 
defaultimpactive
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAnti Social behaviour, whilst not always resulting in reported crime is of major concern to very many communities
default, as evidenced in the visits made by the PCC
default. A summit was held to ensure it was on the agenda of every 
defaultpartner within
default the wider CJ family, including housing providers. A particular focus was to ensure that the tragedy of the Fiona Pilkington case would not 
defaultbe repeated in 
defaultCleveland
default. The outcome of the summit ensured social housing providers now work in partnership with police and 
defaultothers using the legal 
defaultpowers 
defaultavailable
default. This collaborative approach provides a constructive baseline when dealing with repeat offenders
default,
default allowing the needs of the perpetrator to be addressed alongside those of the community. The summit also established a training process to identify repeat victims and assess the difference between ASB and hate crime.
default&#xa0;
default2.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThroughout the first year in office, grappling with CSR10 and then CSR 13 has been a major issue. Working with the Chief Constable and senior staff to develop a policing model that should be sustainable in the longer term, whilst still delivering the 5 priorities of the Police and Crime Plan has been the goal; albeit at a cost of redundancies and compulsory retirements.
default&#xa0;
default3.0default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe role of Commissioners in holding their Chief Constables to accountdefault&#xa0;
default3.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA comprehensive programme of accountability sessions is in operation. Each week the PCC and CC meet to deal with emerging and current issues, postbag, complaints, press, IPCC, HMIC. Each month a strategic performance group involving wider police representation goes into detailed performance trends. In addition is a session each month on a rolling programme of Force Performance, Force Financial, Policy and Organisational issues and ‘Partners and Commissioning’. This ensures that crime trends are central to activity, with the involvement of Community Safety Partnerships designed to ensure that all partners are operating in concert, and to provide third party views on police performance.
default3.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Chief Constable is required to document key decisions with detailed business cases to be considered by the PCC. These are published, as is a forward work plan. Examples include support to G8 and collaboration agreements. With regard to the latter, the Police and Crime Panel have taken the opportunity to scrutinise the PCCs decision making approach and challenged the decision to send resources to 
defaultNorthern Ireland
default to support G8. The PCC then arranged for Keith Bristow of the National Crime Agency to brief panel members and the PCC on the Strategic Policing Requirement. 
default3.3
default              
defaultMystery Shoppers and I
defaultndependent 
defaultC
defaultustody 
defaultV
defaultisitor
defaults are employed to report directly to the PCC and so provide independent views of services delivered by the Chief Constable.
default&#xa0;
default4.0default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011;default&#xa0;default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe following has been submitted to the Home Secretary
default;
defaultStage 2 Transfer
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs required by the above, please find enclosed documentation. This falls within the ‘maximum transfer’ category. Core staff will be retained by the PCC in order to fulfil the statutory role, plus those staff needed to manage the contractual and ancillary arrangements (with particular regard to the extensive outsourced services), and functions that may not be delegated to the Chief Constable.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe submission details only arrangements for staff, with discussions underway on the future scheme of governance, to be completed well before April. The submission is based on the three principles of setting out clarity of roles, enshrining operational independence for the Chief Constable, and conformance with the Policing Protocol. It allocates staffing to enable the PCC to fulfil the duties of S17 of the Protocol, and the S20 ‘wider responsibility for the enhancement of the delivery of criminal justice’ in Cleveland, without duplication or excessive cost. It does not facilitate any involvement of the PCC in operational policing, with all relevant staff in the employ of the Chief Constable. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt does not detail any proposed changes to the arrangements for contracts, pensions, estates, assets and liabilities. These require further considerable detailed work which is underway. It is based on the assumption that the issue of pension arrangements, and associated liabilities, for transferred staff will be resolved by April.
default&#xa0;
default4.2 Before April arrangements will be in place for resources to be shared between PCC and CC. This will include for example, HR, media, legal. For this reason, the notion of a ‘cost of a PCC’ is of very limited value.
default&#xa0;
