default7.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFollowing concerns raised by rural communities regarding the police response to rural issues, several initiatives have been developed. This has culminated in the PCC joint hosting the North East Rural Crime Conference with the Durham PCC. The event was aimed at police forces and organisations across Cleveland, Durham, North Yorkshire, and Northumbria, and highlighted the progress made since the last conference. This was the first time that Cleveland had hosted the event.
default7.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA 
defaultCriminal Justice Volunteers Fair was held to encourage volunteering
default, not only as special constables, but across
default 
defaultall of
default criminal justice. 
defaultThe PCC brought together organisations such as Victim Support, My Sisters Place
default (DV service)
default, 
defaultDTV
default Probation Service, CPS
default, Unite mediation services,
default the Prince’s Trust, and Cleveland Police
default. 16 organisations were represented with some
default 
default900 potential volunteers identified.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe event illustrated how volunteers already make an impact in the criminal justice service as well as highlighting volunteering opportunities
default and showing how the various agencies together support an important area
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe College of Policing noted “The Criminal Justice Volunteer Fair was the first of its type anywhere in England and it was the by far the best example of community and collaborative working.”
